---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

// CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved

const data = {
  metaTitle: 'Retail Inventory & POS System — All Webbed Labs',
  metaDescription: 'How we helped an 8-store Victorian outdoor retail chain replace disconnected legacy POS systems with a unified inventory and point-of-sale platform — cutting stockouts by 52% and enabling click and collect for the first time.',
  industry: 'Retail & E-Commerce',
  tags: ['React', 'Node.js', 'Barcode Scanning', 'Xero Integration', 'Shopify Sync'],
  title: 'Retail Inventory & POS System',
  summary: 'An 8-store Victorian outdoor and camping retail chain had eight different POS systems, no shared inventory visibility, and a shrinkage problem no one could quantify. We built a unified platform that finally let the business see itself clearly — and make stocking decisions based on real data.',
  heroImageDescription: 'Store manager view on a tablet showing real-time stock levels across all 8 store locations, with a barcode scan interface on an adjacent POS terminal in the foreground',

  clientOverview: 'A specialty outdoor and camping retail chain operating eight stores across Victoria — Melbourne CBD, three suburban locations and four regional stores — with 120 staff across all sites. The business has been operating for fourteen years, starting as a single Melbourne CBD store and expanding through acquisition of two smaller regional chains in addition to organic growth. Each store carries between 3,500 and 6,000 SKUs, with significant seasonal variation in demand across the outdoor, camping, and activewear categories.',
  clientSize: '8 stores, 120 staff, 3,500–6,000 SKUs per store',
  clientLocation: 'Victoria (Melbourne and regional)',

  pullQuote: 'I used to get calls from store managers on a Saturday saying they\'d sold out of a tent that I knew was sitting in our Bendigo store. We just had no way to move it or even tell the customer where to get it. That\'s over now.',
  pullQuoteAuthor: 'General Manager — Retail Operations',
  pullQuoteRole: 'Victorian Outdoor Retail Chain',

  challenge: [
    'The business\'s growth through acquisition had created a technology landscape that reflected its history rather than any deliberate decision. The original Melbourne CBD store ran one POS system; the two acquired regional chains had each brought their own, different systems; newer stores had been set up with whatever the operations manager at the time had been able to source quickly. By the time we came in, there were three entirely different POS platforms in active use across eight stores, each with its own database, its own end-of-day process, and its own approach to product catalogues.',
    'Inventory management happened at the store level. Each store manager did a manual stocktake — walking the floor with a clipboard or a handheld barcode scanner connected to a standalone spreadsheet — on a weekly basis. These counts were emailed to the head office operations team, who manually consolidated them into a master spreadsheet. The consolidated spreadsheet was typically 72 hours behind reality by the time anyone looked at it, and the process of consolidation introduced enough transcription errors that the operations manager had learned not to trust individual line items, only broad category-level totals.',
    'The Shopify online store was operating as a completely separate business from a fulfilment perspective. Products listed online had their own inventory numbers, manually maintained by a single staff member whose other job was marketing. When an item sold out in the online store, she updated the listing. When an item sold out in stores but was still available at another location, nobody told the online store. The result was a significant number of orders that couldn\'t be fulfilled, requiring refunds and apology emails — a customer experience problem the founder found genuinely distressing.',
    'Purchase orders were managed in spreadsheets by the operations team, sent to suppliers by email, and tracked on a shared drive that had accumulated years of naming conventions and folder structures. The operations team had a reasonable intuitive grasp of demand for their top-selling lines, but slower-moving or seasonal items were frequently over-ordered at one location and under-stocked at another with no systematic way to identify and correct the imbalance. The general manager estimated that click and collect — a feature regularly requested by customers on the website — was simply impossible to offer credibly without a shared inventory system.',
    'Shrinkage was the issue nobody liked to discuss. The store managers knew it was happening — occasional spot counts would reveal discrepancies — but without accurate baseline inventory data, it was impossible to quantify. Were missing items theft, receiving errors, or simply mistakes in the manual count? The business had no way to answer that question. The general manager suspected it was material but had never had the data to make the case internally for investing in loss prevention.',
  ],

  whyUs: [
    'The general manager had evaluated two off-the-shelf retail management platforms before approaching us. Both solved most of the inventory visibility problem but neither integrated with Xero — the business\'s accounting platform — in a way that met their needs. One required migrating their Xero account to a different chart of accounts structure; the other offered only a one-way sync that would have left the accounts team doing manual reconciliation work. These were deal-breakers. The business\'s accountant was emphatic that any new system had to work cleanly with Xero, not around it.',
    'We were recommended by their Xero implementation partner, who knew we\'d done a number of retail integrations. Our initial proposal was the only one that gave them a clear picture of exactly how the Xero integration would work at a transaction level — not just "syncs with Xero" as a selling point, but a detailed description of how sales, refunds, purchase orders, and adjustments would flow between the retail system and the accounting layer. That specificity gave the general manager and the accountant the confidence to proceed.',
  ],

  approach: [
    'The first thing we did was spend time in each store type: one large-format suburban store, one regional store, and the Melbourne CBD flagship. We were looking for the specifics of how the POS worked in practice — not the theory of how it was supposed to work. In the CBD store, the checkout process was different from the regional stores because of the product mix and because city customers behaved differently (more browsing, more price-conscious, more likely to ask about online availability). These differences mattered for how we designed the POS interface.',
    'We mapped every integration point the business needed: Xero for accounts, Shopify for online orders, the existing barcode scanner hardware (which the business wanted to retain rather than replace — a reasonable cost concern), and the supplier EDI system used by two of their major outdoor gear suppliers. Understanding the full integration landscape before writing a specification prevented scope creep later, because we could make architectural decisions that accommodated all of them from the start.',
    'The product catalogue consolidation was the most unglamorous but most important early task. Three POS systems had produced three product databases, each with different SKU structures, different naming conventions for the same products, and different approaches to variants (colour and size, in the case of apparel and footwear). We built a data consolidation tool that the operations team used over four weeks to merge and deduplicate the catalogue. We provided the tool; they provided the domain knowledge. Some products had to be manually resolved because the same physical item had been entered with completely different product names in different systems. This wasn\'t exciting work, but skipping it would have made everything downstream unreliable.',
    'Barcode scanning hardware compatibility was a constraint we took seriously. The business had invested in a mix of handheld Zebra scanners and desktop barcode readers that were less than two years old. We designed the inventory system to work with these devices over both Bluetooth and USB, using a standard HID interface that required no custom drivers — meaning the hardware the stores already owned worked with the new system without modification.',
  ],

  solution: [
    'The core system is a React application serving as both the POS interface and the back-office inventory management tool. The POS view is optimised for speed: a product search bar (by name, SKU or barcode scan), a quick-add basket, and a payment processing interface. The design was informed by watching experienced cashiers at each store type — the CBD store needed quick keyboard shortcuts that experienced staff could use to bypass mouse-driven navigation; regional stores prioritised the barcode scanning workflow. Both needs were accommodated in a single interface with configurable display modes.',
    'Inventory is managed centrally and updated in real time. Every scan at any POS terminal immediately decrements the relevant location\'s stock count. Stock transfers between locations are managed through a transfer workflow: the originating store scans items out, the receiving store scans them in, and the system tracks the in-transit quantity separately so the inventory picture is always accurate even during the physical movement of stock. This solved the "tent sitting in Bendigo while Melbourne is out of stock" problem the general manager had described.',
    'The Shopify integration is bidirectional. Inventory levels in the central system push to Shopify in near real time (typically within two minutes of a sale). Online orders pull into the central system and can be assigned to a fulfilment location — either the warehouse or a specific store if that store holds the stock. Click and collect, which the business had never been able to offer, became a standard fulfilment option. In the first three months after launch, 17% of online orders were fulfilled as click and collect, which had been essentially zero before.',
    'Xero integration was built as a clean financial data feed. At the end of each trading day, sales totals by payment type, refunds, and cost of goods entries are posted to Xero automatically. Purchase orders raised in the inventory system create corresponding purchase entries in Xero when received. The chart of accounts mapping was set up in collaboration with the business\'s accountant, and the integration was validated against four weeks of historical transactions before go-live to confirm that the numbers matched.',
    'Reporting was built to answer the questions the general manager and operations team actually had, rather than as a generic dashboard. The most-used reports in the first six months were: stock-on-hand by location and category, slow movers (items with no sales in 30+ days), fast movers approaching reorder point, shrinkage variance (expected vs actual based on sales and received stock), and supplier delivery performance (ordered vs received on time). These were surfaced on a role-specific dashboard that staff saw when they logged in, rather than buried in a reports menu.',
  ],

  implementation: [
    'The implementation was staggered across stores over seven weeks. We started with the warehouse and two suburban stores — these were our pilot locations, chosen because they had the most experienced staff and the highest volume of transactions to test against. The first week in each pilot store, the old POS ran in parallel with the new system; at the end of each day, we reconciled the two transaction totals. Discrepancies were almost all accounted for by timing differences in the close-of-day process rather than system errors, but the parallel running gave the store managers confidence before the old system was switched off.',
    'Training was delivered on-site at each store, with role-specific sessions: one session for cashiers and sales staff focused on the POS; a separate session for store managers focused on inventory counts, stock transfers and reporting. We found that the most effective training approach was to complete one full day\'s trading together — the trainer present on the floor, staff doing their normal jobs on the new system, with the trainer handling questions in real time rather than in a classroom scenario. This approach was more expensive than a classroom session but produced significantly higher competency on day two.',
    'The regional stores posed a connectivity consideration we hadn\'t fully anticipated. Two of the four regional stores were in areas where internet connectivity was occasionally interrupted during storms. We\'d built the system to operate with a local cache for POS transactions during brief outages, but one store experienced a four-hour outage during a busy weekend three weeks after go-live. The offline mode handled it correctly — transactions queued locally and synced when connectivity returned — but we hadn\'t communicated clearly enough to staff what they would see on screen during an offline period. We resolved this with better in-app offline status indicators and a staff communication before we rolled out to the remaining stores.',
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    'The data consolidation phase — merging the three product catalogues — took twice as long as we\'d estimated, and it was the right call to build time for it properly. When we\'ve seen other retail system projects go wrong, it\'s almost always traceable to dirty data at the foundation: duplicate products, inconsistent variant structures, missing barcode associations. Investing in clean data before launch is less glamorous than the software itself but more important to the outcome.',
    'The product catalogue work also revealed something useful about the business that the general manager hadn\'t known: one of the acquired chains had been operating with a significantly different margin structure on a subset of products, and those products had been invisibly dragging down category-level profitability. The act of consolidating the catalogues and aligning cost of goods data surfaced this. The general manager described this discovery as "worth the entire project cost on its own." We\'d done nothing clever to find it — it appeared naturally when the data was cleaned and consistently structured for the first time.',
    'The staggered rollout — particularly starting with the stores that had the most experienced and enthusiastic staff — was the right approach for a business with significant geographic spread. The early stores became informal references for the later ones. When staff at the regional stores heard from their colleagues that the system worked well, they started the implementation in a positive frame rather than a resistant one. We\'d recommend this pattern for any multi-site retail implementation.',
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    'Twelve months after go-live, the business asked us to build a supplier portal — a web interface that their major suppliers could log into to see purchase orders, confirm deliveries, and update lead times. Two of their five major suppliers had EDI systems that could connect directly; the other three were managing PO correspondence by email and found the manual process error-prone on their end as well. The portal reduced PO communication overhead for both sides and gave the operations team better visibility into expected delivery schedules.',
    'There is active planning for a customer loyalty programme that would sit on top of the POS and inventory system, giving the business its first view of customer purchase history across channels. The Shopify side already captures online purchase data; the gap has been in-store purchases, which are currently anonymous transactions. Building the loyalty layer would give the marketing team the cross-channel customer view they\'ve been asking for since the system went live.',
  ],

  resultsNarrative: 'The quantitative results have been strong, but the more fundamental change is that the business can now see itself clearly. The general manager can look at inventory across all eight stores from any device, at any time, with data that is minutes old rather than days old. That visibility has changed how the business is managed — from reactive to proactive — in a way that is difficult to capture in a single metric.',

  metrics: [
    { value: '52%', label: 'Reduction in stockouts', context: 'Measured across high-velocity SKUs in first 6 months vs prior year same period' },
    { value: '78%', label: 'Inventory discrepancy reduction', context: 'Variance between system count and physical count at 6-month audit' },
    { value: '3.5 hrs/store/wk', label: 'Manual counting time saved', context: 'Per store reduction in time spent on manual inventory reconciliation' },
    { value: '17%', label: 'Click & collect orders', context: 'Share of online orders fulfilled as click & collect within first 3 months — previously zero' },
    { value: '91%', label: 'Reduction in supplier order errors', context: 'PO discrepancies down from ~4 per week to under 1 per fortnight' },
    { value: '+2.3pp', label: 'Gross margin improvement', context: 'Percentage point improvement driven by reduced markdowns and better ordering' },
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: 'React', reason: 'POS interface and admin dashboard — needs fast, interactive UI with offline capability' },
    { name: 'Node.js', reason: 'API server handling real-time inventory sync across all store terminals' },
    { name: 'PostgreSQL', reason: 'Central inventory database with row-level locking for concurrent POS transaction handling' },
    { name: 'Docker + AWS', reason: 'Containerised deployment for consistency across environments; EC2 in Sydney region' },
    { name: 'Barcode Scanner Integration (HID)', reason: 'Standard HID interface compatibility with existing Zebra hardware; no driver changes required' },
    { name: 'Xero API', reason: 'Automated daily financial data posting: sales, refunds, purchase receipts, COGS entries' },
    { name: 'Shopify Storefront API', reason: 'Bidirectional inventory sync and online order fulfilment routing' },
    { name: 'Service Worker (PWA)', reason: 'Offline POS transaction queueing for stores with intermittent connectivity' },
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
      title: 'Wholesale Ordering Portal',
      href: '/case-studies/wholesale-ordering-portal',
      industry: 'Retail & E-Commerce',
      summary: 'An Australian food manufacturer eliminated manual order processing with a B2B portal handling $2.3M in monthly orders with zero manual data entry.',
    },
    {
      title: 'Customer Loyalty & Personalisation Platform',
      href: '/case-studies/customer-loyalty-personalisation',
      industry: 'Retail & E-Commerce',
      summary: 'An Australian online fashion retailer deployed an AI-driven loyalty platform that increased repeat purchase rate by 33% in the first quarter.',
    },
    {
      title: 'Warehouse Management System',
      href: '/case-studies/warehouse-management-system',
      industry: 'Logistics & Transport',
      summary: 'A 3PL provider processing 1,200 orders daily replaced a legacy WMS with a barcode-driven system that reduced pick errors by 78%.',
    },
  ],

  relatedServices: [
    { title: 'Custom App Development', href: '/services/custom-app-development' },
    { title: 'API Development & Integration', href: '/services/api-development' },
    { title: 'Retail Software', href: '/services/retail-software' },
    { title: 'Database Architecture', href: '/services/database-architecture' },
  ],
};
